The Chapel Hill Denham Nigeria Infrastructure Debt Fund marked the second anniversary of its inception by delivering over 55% total returns to its unit holders over the period. It also announced its eight consecutive quarterly distributions, of N4.34 per unit for the second quarter of 2019. With the Q2 quarterly distribution, the Fund has distributed a total sum of N4.67 billion in cash (N33.86/unit) to NIDF unit holders since inception. Speaking on the progress made, the Chief Executive Officer of NIDF, Chapel Hills Denham, Amdahl Rai explained that its current portfolio of N31bn includes a dozen infrastructure loans with twenty underlying projects and businesses. He said the projects are in multiple sectors including power generation, energy infrastructure, transportation, telecom and social infrastructure, and spread across the country. NSIA invests in Chapel Hill Denham infrastructure debt fund Pension funds: Fears of investing in infrastructure development Still of FCTâ€™s land swap policy Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin